Fluid Dynamics I, Fall 1998         Fluid dynamics         Fall 2007       Professor Stephen Childress.       Wednesday, 9:30-11:20 am in Room 813 WWH       Office Hours: TBA.       This course is a new one-semester fluids course that will cover incompressible fluid flow as well as the basics of gas dynamics. will discuss basic fluid dynamics, both physical and theoretical aspects. Notes are being prepared and will be handed out. See "books" below for text and reserve books for supplemental reading.           Materials and Content            Books        Videos              Tentative syllabus   Note: Click on a lecture to get topics and reading assignments.       Lecture 1: Eulerian and Lagrangian descriptions of a fluid.    Lecture 2: Conservation of mass and momentum.    Lecture 3:  Dynamics of an inviscid fluid.    Lecture 4:  Euler flows and vorticity.    Lecture 5:  Vorticity continued. Potential flow begun.       Lecture 6:  Potential flow continued.       Lecture 7:    Calculation of virtual mass. The lifting airfoil. Thrust production in flapping flight.       Lecture 8:  Models of drag in two dimensions. Prandtl's lifting-line theory of the 3D wing.    Lecture 9: Navier-Stokes equations. The stress tensor. Elementary solutions    Lecture 10: Low Reynolds number flow.    Lecture 11: High Reynolds number flow: boundary layers.       Lecture 12: The energy equation       Lecture 13:  Gas dynamics in one space dimension.       Lecture 14:    Shocks.
